notesStmt.note: Ricci, S. de. Census of medieval and Renaissance manuscripts in the United States and Canada, SM.13a

msContents.summary: Contains an incomplete text of the Book of Rhetoric Addressed to Herennius, a complete Latin rhetoric often included in the corpus of Cicero's works.

msItem.title: Ad Herennium rhetorica manuscript, 15th century / Marcii Tullii Ciceronis.

respStmt.persName: Bivero, Gundisalvus de, bishop of Salamanca.
Allen, Henry Ellis, 1807 or 1808- former owner.
Smedley, William T. (William Thomas), 1851-1934, former owner.
Folger, Emily C. J. (Emily Clara Jordan), 1858-1936, former owner.

msItem.title: Rhetorica ad Herennium.
msItem.incipit: ... vesperi advenit simo ubi advenit mettarum insidias fecit postquam fecit vim in loco attulit. Rem dilucide ...
msItem.explicit: Hec omnia adipiscemus, si rationes preceptionis diligencia consequamur executacionis. [rubr.] Laus tibi, Christe, quam liber explicit iste Marcii Tullii Ciceronis ad Herennium rhetorica feliciter explicit. Iohannes. [f. 114v]

p.catchwords: Horizontal catchwords are centered and enclosed in a rectangular shape throughout.

layoutDesc.layout: Written in 21 long lines (dimensions of written space: 75 x 55 mm); below the first line; frame ruled in red.

binding.p: In limp Spanish vellum wrapper, possibly 15th century, attached to text block with leather strips; traces of leather ties; red edges. Medieval manuscript fragments used in binding.

origin.p: Probably copied in Italy in the 15th century, perhaps for Gundisalvus de Bivero, bishop of Salamanca, who gave it as a gift (de Ricci). Could also be Spanish or French; 15th century

history.provenance: Formerly owned by Henry Allen (Henrici Alani, bookplate); and Smedley (bookplate). Purchased as part of the Smedley Collection in 1924 by Henry Clay Folger.
